Replace the hardcoded fallback chain in SurfaceShell.openFile with a registry-aware chain that ends in EmptyFilePanel when nothing matches. Closes the 'excludeDefaults: [filesystem] still leaks ghost tabs' hole flagged by codex round-2 P1.

## Why current code fails

Verified packages/workspace/src/components/chat/SurfaceShell.tsx:81-108:

```ts
function fallbackComponentForPath(path: string): string {
  const ext = path.split('.').pop()?.toLowerCase()
  if (ext === 'md' || ext === 'markdown') return 'markdown-editor'
  if (ext === 'csv' || ext === 'tsv') return 'csv-viewer'
  return 'code-editor'
}

function resolvePanelForPath(path, registry): string {
  const filename = ...
  const resolved = registry.resolve(filename)
  if (resolved) return resolved.id
  const fallback = fallbackComponentForPath(path)
  if (registry.has(fallback)) return fallback
  // Last-ditch: hand back the first registered panel that accepts files at all.
  return fallback   // ← BUG: returns the literal id even if not registered
}
```

Last-ditch comment is misleading; it just returns the fallback id. So when filesystem is excluded, opening any file picks 'code-editor' — but 'code-editor' isn't registered → blank tab.

## Solution

```ts
function fallbackComponentForPath(path: string): string {
  // unchanged — returns a HINT id, not a guaranteed-registered one
}

function resolvePanelForPath(path, registry): string {
  const resolved = registry.resolve(path)   // pass FULL path (B8 prereq)
  if (resolved) return resolved.id
  const fallback = fallbackComponentForPath(path)
  if (registry.has(fallback)) return fallback
  // No matching panel anywhere. Open EmptyFilePanel — registered as core.
  return 'empty-file-panel'
}
```

## Add EmptyFilePanel core component

```tsx
// packages/workspace/src/panels/EmptyFilePanel.tsx (NEW)
import type { PaneProps } from "../registry/types"
export function EmptyFilePanel({ params }: PaneProps<{ path: string; ext?: string }>) {
  const { path, ext } = params
  return (
    <div className="empty-file-panel">
      <h3>No editor for <code>{path}</code></h3>
      <p>Install or enable a plugin that handles {ext ? `*.${ext}` : 'this file type'}.</p>
    </div>
  )
}
```

Register as a CORE panel (NOT in any plugin) at WorkspaceProvider mount:

```ts
panelRegistry.register('empty-file-panel', {
  id: 'empty-file-panel',
  title: 'Unsupported file',
  component: EmptyFilePanel,
  source: 'builtin',
  // no filePatterns — only opened explicitly via openFile fallback
})
```

It does NOT participate in pattern resolution (no filePatterns). Only opened by the fallback chain.

## Acceptance criteria

- [ ] EmptyFilePanel component added to packages/workspace/src/panels/
- [ ] Registered as core panel at id 'empty-file-panel' (NOT in filesystemPlugin)
- [ ] resolvePanelForPath returns 'empty-file-panel' when registry resolution + extension fallback both miss
- [ ] Opening a file with no matching panel renders EmptyFilePanel showing the path + ext
- [ ] excludeDefaults: ['filesystem'] + opening 'foo.ts' → EmptyFilePanel (NOT a blank/broken tab)

## Tests

- Unit: resolvePanelForPath('foo.xyz', registryWithoutXyz) returns 'empty-file-panel'
- Unit: resolvePanelForPath('foo.ts', registryWithCodeEditor) returns 'code-editor' (no fallback needed)
- Unit: resolvePanelForPath('foo.ts', registryWithoutCodeEditor) returns 'empty-file-panel'
- Integration: WorkspaceProvider with excludeDefaults: ['filesystem'] → SurfaceShell.openFile('foo.ts') opens EmptyFilePanel
- E2E: visiting an app with excluded filesystem and opening a file shows the 'No editor for X' message

## Dependencies

- B8 (path-aware resolver) — touches the same SurfaceShell.tsx code path; logical to land alongside

## Considerations

- EmptyFilePanel is COSMETIC — nothing user-facing depends on its exact text. But the existence of the fallback is contractual (excludeDefaults must be honest).
- Don't accidentally let EmptyFilePanel match files via filePatterns; it's only opened by the explicit fallback.
- This doesn't substitute for a plugin handling .xyz files; it just prevents broken UX when nothing handles them.

Refactor CommandPalette to source its file/data search results from the CatalogRegistry instead of the dead-prop fileSearchFn / onOpenFile (which WorkspaceProvider mounts CommandPalette without — verified codex round-2 P1).

## Existing state (verified)

CommandPalette.tsx still declares fileSearchFn?: (q: string) => string[] and onOpenFile?: (path: string) => void as props (lines ~38, 165). But WorkspaceProvider mounts <CommandPalette/> WITHOUT passing them. So today the file-search path is dead — only command-mode (toggled by ⌘K then '>' or similar) actually works.

## Solution

Drop fileSearchFn / onOpenFile props entirely. Use useCatalogs() to enumerate registered catalogs, then route searches through each catalog's adapter.search(query):

```tsx
// packages/workspace/src/components/CommandPalette.tsx
import { useCatalogs } from "../plugin/useCatalogs"

export function CommandPalette({ open, onOpenChange, ...rest }: CommandPaletteProps) {
  const catalogs = useCatalogs()
  const commandRegistry = useCommandRegistry()
  const [searchQuery, setSearchQuery] = useState('')
  const [isCommandMode, setIsCommandMode] = useState(false)

  // ... existing layout, but results pull from catalogs

  // For each catalog, call adapter.search(query); display by catalog group
  const catalogResults = useMemo(() => {
    if (isCommandMode || !searchQuery) return []
    return catalogs.map(cat => ({
      catalog: cat,
      rows: cat.adapter.search(searchQuery),  // may be sync or returning Promise
    }))
  }, [isCommandMode, searchQuery, catalogs])

  // Render: command results when in command mode; catalog results grouped by label
  // On click: catalog row → catalog.onSelect(row); command → command.run()
  // Both add to Recent (B13b/c)
}
```

## Breaking change

CommandPaletteProps loses fileSearchFn and onOpenFile. Document as Breaking Change #1 in release notes (B19). External callers who somehow passed these props will fail to type-check; that's fine since they were dead-mounted in production.

## Catalog search async handling

ExplorerAdapter.search may be sync or async — both shapes exist. Wrap in a Promise.resolve so the rendering path unifies. Show loading shimmer while pending; render results when resolved.

## Acceptance criteria

- [ ] CommandPaletteProps no longer declares fileSearchFn / onOpenFile
- [ ] Palette renders catalog results from useCatalogs(); grouped by catalog.label
- [ ] Empty search query in non-command mode shows Recent (B13b)
- [ ] Non-empty search query → adapter.search per catalog; results displayed
- [ ] Selecting a catalog row calls catalog.onSelect(row) AND adds to Recent
- [ ] Selecting a command runs command.run AND adds to Recent (per B13b polymorphic Recent)
- [ ] WorkspaceProvider mounts <CommandPalette /> with no removed-prop diff (it was already passing none)

## Tests

- Unit: render <CommandPalette> wrapped in <WorkspaceProvider plugins={[testPluginWithCatalog]}> → typing in palette calls testCatalog.adapter.search
- Unit: selecting a catalog row → catalog.onSelect called with the row; palette closes
- Integration: when no plugin contributes catalogs, palette shows command results only (no broken empty state)

## Dependencies

- B5 (CatalogRegistry + useCatalogs)
- B6 (CommandRegistry subscribe — palette re-renders when commands register late)

## Considerations

- The OLD imperative-prop path is dead in production; no regression risk for current users.
- This bead handles the SEARCH path. Recent path is split into B13b (polymorphic shape) + B13c (localStorage migration).
- Catalog adapters that throw should not crash the palette — wrap in try/catch and show an inline error indicator per catalog group.

Migrate the existing 'boring-ui-v2:command-palette:recent' localStorage key from the legacy string-list shape to the new RecentEntry[] discriminated-union shape. One-time, on first load after this change ships.

## Today's storage shape

Verified packages/workspace/src/components/CommandPalette.tsx:34, :59-60:

```
boring-ui-v2:command-palette:recent → JSON.stringify(string[])
```

The strings are mostly file paths ('src/foo.ts') but some are 'cmd:foo' (for commands; the type-mix bug). Lengths vary.

## Migration strategy (run once on palette mount)

```ts
function migrateRecent(): RecentEntry[] {
  const raw = localStorage.getItem('boring-ui-v2:command-palette:recent')
  if (!raw) return []
  let parsed: unknown
  try { parsed = JSON.parse(raw) } catch { return [] }
  if (!Array.isArray(parsed)) return []

  const migrated: RecentEntry[] = []
  for (const entry of parsed) {
    if (typeof entry !== 'string') continue   // already migrated or malformed
    if (entry.startsWith('cmd:')) {
      const commandId = entry.slice(4)
      migrated.push({
        type: 'command',
        commandId,
        titleSnapshot: commandId,             // best-effort; will be replaced if command resolves
        selectedAt: Date.now(),
      })
    } else {
      // Treat as file path → file catalog entry
      migrated.push({
        type: 'catalog',
        catalogId: 'files',
        rowId: entry,
        rowSnapshot: { id: entry, label: entry } as any,   // minimal row; FileTree adapter will accept
        selectedAt: Date.now(),
      })
    }
  }
  // Persist migrated shape
  localStorage.setItem('boring-ui-v2:command-palette:recent', JSON.stringify(migrated))
  return migrated
}
```

If parse-error, returns empty. If shape is already RecentEntry[] (re-runs after migration), nothing falls through (entries aren't strings; for-of skips). Safe to re-run.

## Acceptance criteria

- [ ] On first palette open after this lands: legacy string array migrates in-place
- [ ] 'cmd:foo' entries become {type:'command', commandId:'foo', titleSnapshot:'foo'}
- [ ] Plain-path entries become {type:'catalog', catalogId:'files', rowId:path, rowSnapshot:{id,label}}
- [ ] After migration, localStorage holds the new shape
- [ ] Re-running migration on the new shape is a no-op (idempotent)
- [ ] Malformed JSON / non-array → migration returns empty list, doesn't throw

## Tests

- Unit: migrateRecent with legacy ['src/a.ts', 'cmd:foo', 'src/b.ts'] → 3 entries: catalog, command, catalog
- Unit: migrateRecent with already-migrated shape → returns same shape unchanged (idempotent)
- Unit: migrateRecent with corrupt JSON → returns []
- Unit: migrateRecent with mixed (some legacy strings, some objects) → handles each correctly
- Integration: mount palette with seeded legacy localStorage → entries appear in Recent in correct branches

## Dependencies

- B13b (polymorphic RecentEntry shape defined)

## Considerations

- This is intentionally lossy on the command branch: titleSnapshot becomes commandId because we don't have the actual title in the legacy shape. On first render after migration, if the command is registered, the renderer can read the live title from CommandRegistry; if not, the commandId is shown. Acceptable.
- DON'T abort on first malformed entry — skip individuals, keep the rest. Robustness for users with weird state.
- Migration runs ONCE; subsequent palette opens just JSON.parse the new shape directly.

Implement per-plugin React error boundaries so a buggy plugin can never crash the workspace shell. Every plugin contribution that renders React (panels, catalog row renderers, chat-suggestion cards) is wrapped in <PluginErrorBoundary pluginId={id}>.

## Why this exists (v7.2 — Revision 1 from planning-workflow review)

PLUGIN_MODEL v7.1 §Error model claimed 'a misbehaving plugin can never crash the workspace, but it can produce degraded UX' — but didn't implement isolation. Today: a panel from plugin X that throws bubbles up to whatever React error boundary is closest, which may be at the app root → crashes everything.

This bead makes the claim true.

## Implementation

```tsx
// packages/workspace/src/plugin/PluginErrorBoundary.tsx (NEW)
import { Component, type ReactNode, type ErrorInfo } from 'react'
import { ErrorChip } from '../components/ErrorChip'
import { useWorkspaceContext } from '../WorkspaceProvider'

interface Props {
  pluginId: string
  contributionKind: 'panel' | 'catalog-row' | 'chat-suggestion'
  contributionId?: string
  children: ReactNode
}

interface State {
  error: Error | null
}

export class PluginErrorBoundary extends Component<Props, State> {
  state: State = { error: null }

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error: Error): State {
    return { error }
  }

  componentDidCatch(error: Error, info: ErrorInfo): void {
